on rates corresponding\nto mean gas disc lifetimes between 3 Myr and 8 Myr.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Mar 2023 17:21:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 16 Mar 2023 17:39:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-24"}
{"id":"2303.07298","submitter":"Carl Johan Peter Johansson","authors":"Carl Johan Peter Johansson","title":"Wild solutions to scalar Euler-Lagrange equations","comments":"24 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study very weak solutions to scalar Euler-Lagrange equations associated\nwith quadratic convex functionals. We investigate whether $W^{1,1}$ solutions\nare necessarily $W^{1,2}_{\\operatorname{loc}}$, which would make the theories\nby De Giorgi-Nash and Schauder applicable. We answer this question positively\nfor a suitable class of functionals. This is an extension of Weyl's classical\nlemma for the Laplace equation to a wider class of equations under stronger\nregularity assumptions. Conversely, using convex integration, we show that\noutside this class of functionals, there exist $W^{1,1}$ solutions of locally\ninfinite energy to scalar Euler-Lagrange equations. In addition, we prove an\nintermediate result which permits the regularity of a $W^{1,1}$ solution to be\nimproved to $W^{1,2}_{\\operatorname{loc}}$ under suitable assumptions on the\nfunctional and solution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Mar 2023 17:23:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-14"}
